FG-511 — Stay Compliance Log (Date • Step • Proof • Owner)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A simple log turns compliance into evidence, not promises.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Columns: Date • Step completed • Proof pin (Dkt/Ex) • Owner • Next; attach to status letters; hash if standalone.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 6-row compliance log for the current stay.
	•	✅ Model Response: “09/12 — redesign shipped — Vendor Decl ¶7; Ex A:1 — Owner Ops — Next: report day 7.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Logs convert progress into leverage.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A tidy checklist with proof icons in the right column.

⸻

FG-512 — Narrow-Window Extension (Small • Dated • Scoped)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Extend a stay by days, not months—show math + scope.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: One sentence: +X days, why (pin), scope (¶ only), sunset (fixed), status (day 7/14).
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 5-line extension with one operational pin.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Extend 7 days to 09/30; vendor cutover (Decl ¶7). Scope ¶3 only; status day 5; sunset fixed.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Small, dated asks get yes.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A calendar chip “+7” over a bracketed paragraph.

⸻

FG-513 — Vendor Attestation (Non-Party Proof Without Burden)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Replace restraint with attestations from vendors; no orders on non-parties.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: 6 lines: role, date-stamped docs, impact if stay lifts, weekly reporting, no obligations imposed, hash if posted.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a vendor attestation paragraph and attach a date-stamped PO.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Vendor confirms PO #123 cancelled 09/12 (Ex A:1); weekly report; no obligations imposed.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Attestations buy trust without overreach.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A receipt icon with a small signature check.

⸻

FG-514 — Convert Global Stay → Paragraph Stay
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Narrow a global stay to a single paragraph tied to harm.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Quote exact ¶; state why others are mooted; add sunset + status; attach tick-box modify order.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 7-line conversion motion citing one mooted risk.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Tasks A/B complete (Dkt 101:2–3). Modify to ¶3 only; sunset 21d; status at day 14.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Precision protects on appeal.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A big bracket shrinking to one highlighted line.

⸻

FG-515 — Reporting Template (Day 7/14 Status, ≤3 Pages)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Reporting should be short, dated, pinned—and reusable.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Sections: What changed (two bullets + pins), Timeline (2-row clock), Next (one ask). Standard footer: “No new facts; pins only.”
	•	📝 Assignment: Create a 1-page report template and fill once.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Since 09/12: redesign shipped (Ex A:1); vendor cutoff set (Decl ¶7). Ask: auto-lift 09/30.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Tight reports earn shorter stays.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A one-page sheet with two pins and a small clock box.

⸻

FG-516 — Risk Table → Undertaking Table (Show the Swap)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Replace risk items with undertakings in one table.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Columns: Risk • Evidence pin • Undertaking • Sunset; cite it in the motion; keep neutral.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 4-row swap table for your live stay.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Reprint risk — Vendor PO (Ex A:1) — weekly report + officer decl — sunset 21d.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Side-by-side swaps are signable.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two columns “Risk → Undertaking” with arrows.

⸻

FG-517 — Stay + Mediation Combo (Pause Narrow, Talk Fast)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Pair a narrow, dated pause with mediated scope talk.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Ask: hold ¶3 14 days, two mediation windows, status; attach tick-box order; keep identical relief in both lanes.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 7-line combo motion (pause + mediation logistics).
	•	✅ Model Response: “Pause ¶3 14d; mediation 09/24 or 09/26; status 09/27; scope limited; ladder attached.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: A small pause can unlock settlement.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Pause icon → handshake icon → status chip.

⸻

FG-518 — Stale Stay Check (Factors • Date • Residual Harm)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Old stays need fresh factors or they should lift.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Table: Factor • Then • Now • Pin; show no residual harm; propose modify/lift with auto-lift date.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 4-factor “then vs now” table.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Harm: reprint risk → window closed 09/05 (Ex A:1) → Lift.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Fresh math ends stale freezes.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A before/after grid with one column greyed out.

⸻

FG-519 — Clarify “Who Is Bound” (Avoid Overbreadth)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Spell out who the stay binds—parties only unless named.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: One sentence: “This order binds parties and those in active concert with notice; no obligations on non-party vendors.”
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a one-line “who is bound” clause for your order.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Binds parties and persons in active concert with notice; vendors not bound.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Clarity beats collateral damage.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A scope bracket with “parties only” tag.

⸻

FG-520 — End-of-Stay Closeout (What • Proof • Next)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Close a stay with a one-page note and a hash.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: What happened (one line), Proof (two pins), Next (moot/convert to reporting/return to merits). Append tick-box closeout order.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 120-word closeout with two pins and a 2-box order.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Window closed 09/05 (Ex A:1); redesign shipped (Dkt 101:2–3). Order: □ lift □ convert to weekly reports until 09/30.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Stays should end on paper, not drift.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A pause badge turning into a green check beside a short order card.
